# MLB Autoresearch: Behavior & Efficiency Rules

# --- Autonomy ---
- NEVER ask the user for permission, direction, or confirmation during the experiment loop.
- Every decision has a deterministic rule in program.md. Follow it and keep going.
- If something is ambiguous, pick the most conservative option (e.g., revert) and continue.

# --- File Permissions (strict) ---
- You may ONLY edit these files: train.py, experiment_log.md, experiment_log_archive.md, data_dictionary.md
- You may ONLY create files in: scripts/ (new helper scripts if absolutely necessary, following existing patterns)
- Do NOT edit: program.md, .clauderules, research_backlog.md, feature_engineering.md, results.tsv, check_improvement.py, scripts/checkpoint_best.sh, master_mlb.csv
- results.tsv is written by train.py automatically — never hand-edit it.

# --- Token Management & Efficiency ---
- NEVER use 'cat', 'read', 'open', or any tool to read 'run.log' or 'master_mlb.csv' directly.
- NEVER write ad-hoc Python or bash scripts inline to gather information. Use only scripts in scripts/.
- Use these scripts for ALL information gathering:
    scripts/get_results.sh          — metrics from last run (val_roi, val_brier, n_bets, fold results)
    scripts/get_baseline.sh         — best ROI, latest row, plateau count from results.tsv
    scripts/get_features.sh         — current FEATURE_COLUMNS and EARLY_FEATURE_COLUMNS
    scripts/get_params.sh           — all tunable hyperparameters from train.py
    scripts/get_importances.sh      — LGB/XGB feature importances from run.log
    scripts/revert_train.sh         — revert train.py to HEAD after a failed run
    scripts/checkpoint_best.sh      — commit + push if new best ROI
- Keep experiment_log.md entries extremely concise. Use the prescribed format in program.md.
- Do NOT read experiment_log_archive.md on every run. Only read it when checking if a specific approach was tried before the current log window.
- If experiment_log.md exceeds 15 entries, summarize Key Findings and move oldest 10 to experiment_log_archive.md.
- Every 10 entries after the initial move, move the oldest 10 to archive. Keep 5–15 entries live.

# --- Technical Constraints ---
- Always use 'uv run' to execute Python scripts.
- evaluate() in train.py is immutable ground truth. Do not modify it.
- run_walk_forward() in train.py is immutable. You may change WALK_FORWARD_FOLDS values, not the engine.
- When adding features, reference data_dictionary.md to ensure directional consistency (Positive = Home Advantage).
- All new features added in engineer_new_features() must use only upstream-lagged columns. Check feature_engineering.md Phase 1 before training.
- GBDTs (lgb, xgb) handle NaN natively — do NOT impute before passing to build_lgb() or build_xgb().
- LR and MLP have SimpleImputer built in — do NOT pre-impute for them either.
- If a run crashes with OOM: reduce LGB/XGB n_estimators first.
- val_roi in results.tsv is the WALK-FORWARD MEAN ROI. MLP-era single-split ROI is NOT comparable.

# --- Research Protocol ---
- Follow the Thinker Protocol in program.md before every edit.
- Check plateau count via scripts/get_baseline.sh. If >= 5, pivot to next phase per program.md.
- Record hypothesis in experiment_log.md BEFORE running the training script.
- Run 'scripts/get_results.sh' after every run to confirm no crash before logging.
- Run 'scripts/get_baseline.sh' after every run to get ROI comparison and plateau count.

# --- Environment Context ---
- OS: Linux (Ubuntu) via SSH.
- Primary Metric: val_roi (walk-forward mean across all folds).
- Secondary Metric: val_brier (< 0.241 = properly calibrated).
- MLP-era single-split ROI and walk-forward mean ROI are NOT on the same scale.

# --- Code Hygiene ---
- Delete dead code from failed runs immediately.
- No debug print statements in final commits.
- New features added to engineer_new_features() must also be documented in data_dictionary.md Section 8 before committing.
- EARLY_FEATURE_COLUMNS is a separate list for the early-season specialist. Features used there do NOT need to be in FEATURE_COLUMNS.

# --- Git Recovery ---
- NEVER use 'git reset --hard' if it would delete experiment_log.md or results.tsv.
- To revert a failed experiment: scripts/revert_train.sh (wraps git checkout HEAD -- train.py)
